title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum on 1993-02-22
description: Hell In A Bucket-> Sugaree, Walkin' Blues, Althea, When I Paint My Masterpiece, So Many Roads, Cassidy, Don't Ease Me In Saint Of Circumstance-> Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain-> Wave To The Wind-> Drums-> Jam-> The Days Between-> Throwing Stones-> Not Fade Away, E: Knockin' On Heaven's Door

reviews.review_text: who was working the SOUNDBOARD???? very interesting musical show..especially touching Scarlet-Fire..but all of the vocals are muffled and the instruments completely overwhelm the sound..if you just like the music...it's ok..otherwise..not recommended

Great Sound / Bad Mix I concur with the first poster.  The mix is very unstable on Bob and Jerry's guitar.  There are tunes where Bob's guitar is way out in front, but with no Garcia.  Also, Garcia's vocals are very low.  Then on SMR, The mix is low until the rest of the band kicks in, and then the drums are in front of the mix.  You should probably pass on this show, despite it being a very good sounding board, just with a bad mix.

ho hum Very Low energy show. I started listening to it b/c I wanted to hear the debut of Days Between, and got so bored by a minute or two into Scarlet, that I just stopped it. The mix is pretty bad here too, thin vocals, too much Jerry and Phil, little to no Bob, and just a general off-ness to the sound. This one is pretty much a yawner IMHO.

I was there. I was there. I remember the audio being off and Bob waving his hand to the soundboard guys to fix the sound during one of the songs, Wave to the Wind I think.

I went to this show alone. Just moved out of the house at 21 yrs old. I remember being fairly entertained, but thought the show was rather lacking in some respects. Not the best of thirty or so shows. My favorite is Halloween 91. Best ever attended. Luck had it.

I do remember crying during the first version of Days Between for some reason. One of only three shows I caught in 93. From then on it was downhill for the Dead, even though no one wanted to admit it. Very good time in my life and one of the most profound influences I've ever had. Something to tell the grandkids about. Thankyou Jerry.

Oh yeah, I remember some Deadhead chick yelling out "We Love You" really loud from right in front of the stage to the band I believe sometime during second set. Was an eerie situation I remember. Sort of caught the band off gaurd. If you listen closely between songs you can hear it.

Thymer
best night of run This was the best night of the three night run IMHO. Soundboard/mix does'nt do it justice. So much room to dance right up front in PHIL ZONE....Good times...
